North Korea rejects unilateral disarmament without trust
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions deepened its distrust of the United States and under these circumstances the country would not unilaterally abandon its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the World Organization that North Korea had taken “essential action” last year, for example, stopping nuclear and missile tests, demolishing the nuclear test site and committing itself not to proliferate nuclear weapons and technologies.
"But we do not see any corresponding reaction from the US," he said.
“Without confidence in the United States, there is no confidence in our national security, and under these circumstances we will by no means disarm ourselves unilaterally first.”
While Ri repeated familiar North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" approach to denuclearization, in which North Korea was rewarded for successive steps, his statement seemed significant in that it did not reject unilateral denuclearization from the outset, as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri pointed to a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first summit meeting between an incumbent U.S. President and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim had pledged to work on the “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula” while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea’s security.
North Korea seeks an official end to the Korean War led from 1950 to 1953, while the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
In addition, Washington opposes calls for a easing of strict international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'first denuclearization' and increases pressure by sanctions to achieve its goal by coercion, and is even opposed to 'declaring the end of the war'," Ri said.
“The assumption that sanctions can force us to our knees is a brainspin of people who don’t know anything about us.
The problem, however, is that the continued sanctions deepen our distrust."
Ri did not go into plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. head of state had highlighted at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korean head of state Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If South Korea were the other party on the denuclearization issue, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have stopped.”
Nevertheless, the tone of Ris’s speech was enormously different from his speech last year when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to target North Korea’s missiles on the U.S. mainland after “the evil president” called Trump a “missile man” on suicide mission.
This year, Trump, who had threatened the “complete destruction” of North Korea last year, overshadowed Kim at the United Nations with praise for his courage in disarmament moves, but he said there is still a lot of work to be done and the sanctions must remain in force until North Korea denuclearizes.
On Wednesday, Trump said he didn’t have a time frame for it: “Whether it takes two years, three years, or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council must reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday: "The enforcement of the Security Council sanctions must in any case be continued vigorously until we have achieved complete, final and verified denuclearization."
The Security Council has unanimously stepped up sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to financially dry out Pyongyang’s nuclear weapons and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the outskirts of the UN General Assembly and said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip was unsuccessful.
In July, when leaving Pyongyang, he said that progress had been made only to be accused hours later by North Korea of having made “gangster-like demands.”
North Korea vowed this month at a meeting with Moon to dismantle a missile base and a nuclear complex if the United States took “corresponding action.”
He said Kim had told him that the targeted “corresponding measures” were security guarantees that Trump had given in Singapore, as well as steps to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard Students Learn Enough to Sleep in One Course
A new course at Harvard University ensures that all undergraduate students get more sleep this year. This is a measure against the spreading macho culture of keeping up with caffeine and learning all night long.
One scientist has found that students at the world’s leading university are often unnecessary when it comes to taking care of themselves.
The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, and is in his opinion the first such course in the United States.
He was inspired to launch the course after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
“In the end, a girl came to me and asked, ‘Why am I only learning about it now, in my last year?’
According to her words, no one had ever told her how important sleep is. That surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
This year’s first course explained to students how the basics of good sleep habits contribute to academic and athletic performance and also improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university had opted to launch the course after finding that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In a section, students see the image of a room in a dormitory and click on coffee mugs, curtains, training shoes and books, providing information on the effect of caffeine and light, as well as on the effects of lack of sleep on athletic performance and the importance of a sleep routine.
In another section, participants learn that long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, and cancer.
Then, using a map of the university site with interactive symbols, they are encouraged to think about their daily routine.
“We know that it won’t change students’ behavior immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know – just like you have the right to know how the decision to smoke affects your health,” added Professor Czeisler.
The pride of pushing a “night shift” is still widespread, he said, adding that modern technologies and the ever-increasing pressure on students made the lack of sleep a growing problem.
Ensuring enough good sleep should be the “secret weapon” of all students against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, and weight gain could be avoided, as sleep deprivation puts the brain into hunger mode so that they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, having taken one of his courses last year in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and encouraged him to push for a university-wide course.
He hopes that the next step will prompt all postgraduate students to complete a similar study program before starting their studies at the competitive university.
According to Professor Czeisler's recommendation, students should set up an alarm clock for bedtime and wake-up time and be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" that emanates from electronic screens and LED lights and can bring the circadian rhythm out of time, which leads to problems when falling asleep.
