The study, conducted by researchers at the National Trust for Scotland, will track dwarf and mosquito bats as well as the Brown Long Ear and Water Bats at Inverewe Garden in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices are placed at key locations on the property to record the bats’ activities throughout the season.
NHS employees and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations using portable detectors.
In a noise analysis of all images by experts, the frequency of bat calls is determined and determined which species does what.
Subsequently, a map and habitat report is created to create a detailed picture of their behavior at the landscape level.
Rob Dewar, conservation consultant for the NTS, hopes that the results will show which areas of the habitat are most important for the bats and how they are used by each species.
This data will help determine the benefits of habitat management measures, such as the creation of meadows, and show how to preserve forest areas for bats and other related species.
Bat stocks in Scotland and the whole of the United Kingdom have declined significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects sleeping places and leads to loss of habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as can flycatchers and the chemical treatment of building materials or attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not really blind.
However, their ears are more useful than their eyes because of their nocturnal hunting habits when it comes to catching prey.
They use sophisticated echometry to detect insects and obstacles in their trajectory.
The NTS, responsible for the maintenance of over 270 historic buildings, 38 significant gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout Scotland, takes the subject of bats very seriously.
It has 10 trained experts who regularly conduct examinations, sleeper inspections, and sometimes rescue measures.
The organization has even established Scotland’s first and only bat reserve at Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland’s 10 bat species.
Property manager David Thompson explains that the property is the ideal habitat for them.
“Here in Threave we have a great area for bats,” he explains.
“We have the old buildings, many old trees and an excellent habitat.
But there’s a lot we don’t know about bats yet, so here and in other goods we are doing these works that will help us learn more about what bats need to feel comfortable.”
He stresses the importance of first excluding the presence of bats before maintenance work in the goods, as it is possible that the unintentional destruction of a single nesting site could kill up to 400 females and young animals and wipe out the entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, harass them or destroy them or their nesting places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish official of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the population to help.
She explains: “We still have a lot to learn about bats and for many of our species we don’t know what their populations are like.”
